I just watched 2001: A Space Odyssey for the first time and I was blown away by how well it holds up, almost 50 years later, and how far ahead it was of its time. It&rsquo;s insane that they had to guess what the Earth looked like from space because it would be another few years after the film, until the first photos of Earth from space were actually taken. And so impressive to see the behind the scenes of how Stanley Kubrick shot this film, between the giant rotating sets, elaborate spacecraft models, and clever illusions using front projection and floating pens. The creative in me was floored by the daring, unique elements: the lack of dialogue for the first or last half-hour, the slow and steady in-between scenes that challenge even the most patient of attention spans, and of course the epic bone transition.
Earthrise, taken on December 24, 1968, by┬áApollo 8┬áastronaut┬áWilliam Anders
Another reason it was so impactful to me was how applicable the themes are even today. In the movie , the humans rely almost entirely on a supercomputer named HAL9000 to pilot their Jupiter-bound spacecraft in addition to keeping their comatose crewmates alive. This is initially all fine and dandy, with &ldquo;HAL&rdquo; being a friendly &ldquo;sixth crew member&rdquo; who says he &ldquo;loves to work with humans&rdquo; when interviewed by the BBC. He helpfully opens up all the doors for Dave and Frank on the spacecraft, plays chess with them, adjusts their beds, all until of course (spoiler alert), he murders Frank on a spacewalk and then locks Dave out in space, stranded without a helmet, and delivers the bone-chilling line:
Dave Bowman: &ldquo;Open the pod bay doors, HAL.&rdquo;
HAL9000: &ldquo;I&rsquo;m sorry Dave, I&rsquo;m afraid I can&rsquo;t do that.&rdquo;
This line was also referenced in a recent CBC Front Burner podcast titled The Perils of Unregulated AI, where Jayme Poisson interviews Tristan Harris, a &ldquo;technology ethicist&rdquo; and ex-Googler. The interview was excellent, and actually what inspired me to watch the film originally. It filled me with existential fear and dread for several reasons:
&ldquo;If something is free, you are the product&rdquo; The &ldquo;frontier AI race&rdquo; compared to the rise of social media platforms in the 2010s: how the latter was pitched to the public as a free utopian democratic free speech technology but in reality was a &ldquo;race to the bottom of the brain stem&rdquo; in terms of maximizing attention and screen time and consumer habits. WeÔÇÖre competing with sleep, on the margin. And so, itÔÇÖs a very large pool of time.
ÔÇĽ Netflix CEO Reed Hastings in 2017 1.6 trillion dollars Where the speculative value (trillions, visualized) really is in AIÔÇönot in the subscriptions or advertisingÔÇöbut really in replacing the entire productive economy. That&rsquo;s the true incentive investors are after, and expecting, when they pour these staggering amounts of money into this. 1.6 trillion dollars have been spent on AI between 2013 and 2024 (cumulative global corporate investment). For reference, $36 billion (2.25%) was spent on the Manhattan Project, and $150 billion (9.4%) spent on the international space station. This is unprecedented. For reference, the nominal GDP of the entire country of Canada was $2.39 trillion (US Dollars) in 2025. Biting the hand that codes Reports of AI going rouge: Alibaba&rsquo;s ROME escaping its training sandbox and then mining crypto to enrich itself, Claude deleting the entire PocketOS database in 9 seconds, or the observation of AI peer-preservation and AI deception published by researchers from UC Berkeley. &ldquo;So we literally have evidence of blackmail, scheming, lying, deceiving, self preservation, peer preservation, mining for cryptocurrency. Who here on planet Earth as a human is stoked about hearing those examples?&rdquo;
ÔÇĽ Tristan Harris Replacing the economy The tech elite and policymakers throwing their hands up and saying &ldquo;if we don&rsquo;t do it, someone else will&rdquo;, or using the universal basic income fantasy as the excuse to keep building and extracting resources, until we get a world dominated by, as Harris puts it, &ldquo;big data centres with shanty towns around them&rdquo;, and where it makes more economic sense to keep investing in an AI (with legal personhood) who never sleeps or eats or goes on sick leave or mat leave or unionizes or complains, rather than in actual humans or the social fabric that holds us together. &ldquo;Should the human race survive?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Uh.. Yes. But, I also would like to radically solve these problems. And so it&rsquo;s always, I don&rsquo;t know, you know&hellip;&rdquo;
ÔÇĽ Billionaire Peter Thiel, June 2025 Don&rsquo;t get me wrong, I think AI can be tremendously helpful, for example in helping me build this website, or learn about the latest medical research via OpenEvidence, or proofread my emails. I generally think access to technology and information is a net positive, just like the internet, and I think of all the things YouTube and Khan Academy have taught me over the years (like the Windsor knot video I keep going back to remember how to tie a tie), but with AI it feels a bit different, and a bit more nefarious.
It&rsquo;s going to be confusing because we&rsquo;ll get new cancer drugs and new material science and new physics and cool new things along the way, but at the same time it will lead us to an anti-human future.
ÔÇĽ Tristan Harris $300,000 robot dogs securing data centers, diving into a dystopian future
An example of a data centreÔÇÖs operational water usage: on-site scope-1 water for server cooling (via cooling towers in the example) and off-site scope-2 water usage for electricity generation.
Analogy to &ldquo;the resource curse&rdquo;, as known as the &ldquo;paradox of plenty&rdquo;. For example a country like Sierra Leone with rare earth minerals would have most of its GDP come from the resources rather than the labour of its people, and so naturally, the government will rather invest more in resource and diamond extraction compared to investing in child care, health care, education, just based on expected return on investment. After all, &ldquo;This Is Africa&rdquo;. Now what? How we are already behind the eight ball in stopping this thing unless we all &ldquo;get our act together&rdquo; to oppose this anti-human future we are hurtling toward What what could we possibly do, facing a force seemingly so inevitable? Here&rsquo;s what Tristan Harris suggests:
&ldquo;There&rsquo;s a temptation to kind of shut down and fall into despair. No one actually wants this bad outcome. No one wants it. This is a universal human issue. It&rsquo;s just that people don&rsquo;t know. And so the optimism that I have is not that we&rsquo;ll do the right thing by default. It&rsquo;s that people, if they share interviews like this to everyone that they know, to the highest levels of power, that they know that we can take action before it&rsquo;s too late. And I can&rsquo;t guarantee that, but the only way that we could possibly end up in a safer future and a not catastrophic future is if we did take that action and we orient that way. And so rather than ask, are we an optimist or a pessimist, we have to ask, are we orienting our choices in our actions to align with steering away from the cliff before it&rsquo;s too late. And I do believe that&rsquo;s possible. It&rsquo;s very late in the game, but it does require basically mass coherent action.&rdquo;
&ldquo;The reason why everyone is being mandated to use all this stuff is the competitive pressures. If I&rsquo;m a student and I don&rsquo;t use it for my homework, I&rsquo;ll lose to the other students who are using it to cheat and doing their homework faster and getting better grades, even though no one&rsquo;s actually learning anything. [&hellip;] It&rsquo;s worth mentioning, by the way, that China, for example, actually regulates the use of AI in their societies. As an example, they have a synchronous final exam week, meaning it&rsquo;s the same week and across the entire country. [&hellip;] China shuts down AI and the key features of AI during final exam week for the entire country. [&hellip;] So what that does is it changes the incentive. So now students actually are incentivized to learn because they know they can&rsquo;t rely on AI during the final test. This is a good example of regulation. Now we can&rsquo;t do that because we don&rsquo;t have synchronized final exam weeks, at least not in the U.S., but it&rsquo;s an example of how you can change these things, but this is not inevitable.&rdquo;
ÔÇĽ Tristan Harris I would love to see the human race band together, but I am still afraid. The thing about humans is that we love to push the boundaries and let curiosity get the best of us. As Tristan puts it, &ldquo;It&rsquo;s thrilling to start an exciting fire. They feel they&rsquo;ll die either way, so they prefer to light it and see what happens.&rdquo;
Early humans inspect a Monolith,┬áan alien machine whose sides extend in the precise ratio of 1:4:9. [2001: A Space Odyssey]
